    The project is written in Go.

    The code respects the good practices.

    It has test files for unit testing.


Standard.txt Format hold the ascii characters







 _____                 _                           _     _                        
|_   _|               | |                         | |   (_)                       
  | |    _ __    ___  | |_   _ __   _   _    ___  | |_   _    ___    _ __    ___  
  | |   | '_ \  / __| | __| | '__| | | | |  / __| | __| | |  / _ \  | '_ \  / __| 
 _| |_  | | | | \__ \ \ |_  | |    | |_| | | (__  \ |_  | | | (_) | | | | | \__ \ 
|_____| |_| |_| |___/  \__| |_|     \__,_|  \___|  \__| |_|  \___/  |_| |_| |___/ 
                                                                                  
                                                                                  
1- make sure you have installed the main.go, standard.txt and specificline.go file and the go.mod file. and keep the main.go and standard.txt in a folder with any name you want

2-open the terminal and make sure you are in the folder you kept main.go in

3-Pass the text you want to stylize as a command-line argument. For example:

                    go run . "Hello, World!"





